text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Generally, patients in the pre-contemplative state of change don't realise they have a
problematic behaviour.
In our specific context of exercise as a treatment of RCRSP, the patients in this state
typically think their shoulder problem is anatomical, and the solution will be passive
and/or external (rest, massage, injection, surgery…).
Since patients don’t realise there is a problem, providing them a solution is meaningless.
Our position here will be to simply raise doubts.
Pre-Contemplative State
Pre-Contemplative State :
Raising doubts

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: The point of this section is to fight against a patho-anatomical conception of RCRSP.
It is aimed at patients that believe their shoulder condition will improve from passive
modalities.

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: The contemplative state of change is characterised by ambivalence. Patients in this
state are aware of the benefits of changing their behaviour, but they are not ready to
make the change yet and also find advantages in their current situation.
In the case of RCRSP, ambivalence can have many forms : “I understand exercise will help
me… But it hurts !”, “Physical activity is probably great, but after a days’ work I need rest”,

tspan.tspan: “I know my exercise programme will help me, but it’s just not the right time, it will probably

text.tspan: be easier for me next week”. Procrastination is also common at this stage.
Our objective here is to tip the scales !
Contemplative State
Contemplative State :
Ambivalence

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Patients should understand how moving and exercising will help them, and we should
help them engage in active rehabilitation. Those videos are meant to weigh toward
active interventions in the decisional balance.
You can find some more information on this state of change, or go to the videos by
clicking on the arrows.

text.tspan: Pre-Contemplative State :
Raising doubts
The videos provided in this tool can be used independently, but they are
presented here like a path, and they are grouped according to Prochaska
and Diclemente states of change (transtheoterical model).
Don’t worry if you are unfamiliar with this model, it’s mostly used here as a
way to organise the content. This classification is based on the patient’s
state of mind regarding therapeutic exercise and physical activity as a
treatment for RCRSP.
This model has been used a lot to fight against addictive behaviours, but it
can be transposed to physical activity and pain management.
The next slide will be on the pre-contemplative state-of change
The point of this tool is to offer
educationnal videos, that cover different
topics related to exercise and physical
activity for the management of rotator
cuff related shoulder pain (RCRSP).
RCRSP Companion for
Exercise and Physical Activity
This is a presentation of the
different videos, how they relate to
each other and what topic they
cover.
This part will hopefully help you
determine which video is best
suited for your patient at every step
of the rehabilitation.
Preparation state :
Readiness

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Preparation state is the time of decisions, the ambivalence has been resolved. But the
choice can be temporary, and difficulties can rise and postpone action.
There will be no video for this state, as the problems to be alleviated are practical and
very specific to each patient.
The suggested behaviour here is to set goals with our patient, to schedule the exercise
programme and to discuss the practical aspects of it : “When will you be able to do your
exercises ?”,”We should think together of how you will do this programme, which room

tspan.tspan: seems best suited in your place ?”

text.tspan: Action state :
First steps

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: In the action state, the patient has changed behaviour, but moving forward is
demanding and therapists' help can be useful.
In the case of exercising as a treatment of RCRSP, though the patient is engaged in the
active rehabilitation, we should provide support : fostering self-efficacy and positive
reinforcement are useful strategies.
Highlight progress made and emphasize the importance of patient's current
engagement.
Maintenance :
Keep on !

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: The patient has adopted a new behaviour and we should try to help them convert this
to an integrated longer-term change.
This mostly concerns physical activity against sedentary lifestyle. We can still help our
patient, by making him identify situations that could make him doubt or stop being
physically active.
There is no video on this state at this point !
Relapse :
Give support !

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Although relapse isn’t as concerning in our shoulder context as it is in addictive
behaviours, it still can be experienced as a failure and result in a loss of confidence in
one's ability to cope.
We should try to avoid guilt and bring support and motivation to restart a process of
change.
Once again, there is no video on this state at this point !
